Monday came , my father had an attorney and they went to the DAs office and showed the warrant. Obviously, the charges were dropped and she was let out and they found the real woman matching the description of the warrant.

There used to be something in this country called citizen review boards. Basically what they were was a group of people in local municipalities from every walk of life and profession. From the rich to the poor, colored or white it didn't matter. Their job basically entailed a citizen to have the ability to review a police officer's actions. It is part of the founding of this nation to prevent tyranny, to help avoid giving any political office or public service the ability to have control over the citizens to a point that the citizens have no rights. The police didn't have ultimate authority then like they do now. If you had a complaint you could take it to the citizens review board and they could actually remove police officers, mayors, or any elected official in the capacity of public service including employees of those offices. It was based off of the biblical standards of calling on the elders of the community who would refer to the law. People have forgotten that our constitutional structure in this country is based off of one ideal and that is "Lex Rex" which means "the law is King". It prevents any one individual from gaining power and transforming our republic into a tyranny, at least that's the way it used to be. I am so thankful that these guys are doing videos like this, I can only pray that the Black and Hispanic communities will take the time to listen. We cannot defund police officers, they are an integral and important part of our structure. They do need reform however, and power needs to be put back into the local level, at the citizens level. Just like in a trial you aren't found guilty unless 12 of your peers find you guilty, it should also be the same power that is looked upon to review these cases. Judges and police officers have been given too much authority and power, it was never intended to be that way. Judges are put on a bench not to wield the weapon of a gavel against the common man, they're there to be of sound mind and a restrainer against revenge. Their whole job is to ensure that true justice is served both for the victim and the criminal, and justice does not mean making the criminals suffer it means reform which we haven't seen in this country in a long time. Some would say that the courts would be weighed down, but if we returned to the way it was supposed to be set up they wouldn't. We actually don't have enough courthouses or jurisdictions. Each neighborhood or town should have its own municipal court system not one per city or county and cities were never intended to be so big or overpopulated that they couldn't handle a system of justice. We are at the great precipice in this country, the edge of no return but it's not too late if we just gather our thoughts and voice our expectations to our representatives on the state and federal levels. Yes, "representatives" not leaders. That's something else that so many of us have forgotten, these people are not our leaders, they are supposed to be our representatives speaking the hopes and expectations of our voiced concerns and desires not their own.

It's fear, and it's leading to hatred. That doesn't justify hate, but I think awareness and a healthy degree of caution is understandable. What we need is to better hold these gang members with badges accountable. This way other would-be bad actors have an example, and a reason to pay attention when they train on deescalation. I always try to assume the best when I see and think of law enforcement, because they are a necessary piece of civilization. However, I never let myself become too comfortable, because almost anyone can become an officer these days. We've been applying sedatives, instead of treating the wound, and I think we need to start healing. Because I'd say 98% of officers are good people, who just want to do their job and go home to whatever awaits them. We can't keep letting that other 2% decide their image. Better training, better accountability, better law enforcement. Also Floyd's past criminal record needs to stop being used in these kind of arguments, justice is supposed to be blind. An injustice was committed, doesn't matter what Floyd's record was.
